{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627317"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:47:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:47:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17112"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17112"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.64,0.04,0.11,0.02,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9802"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77018"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9802","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9802"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17112"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62524"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5037"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22980"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23109"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77018","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77018"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EClass 1a antiarrhythmic medications are used in the treatment of cardiac arrhythmias. These drugs exert their effects by modifying the function of specific ion channels in cardiac myocytes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of class 1a antiarrhythmic drugs?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blocks sodium channels exclusively","Blocks beta-adrenergic receptors","Blocks calcium channels exclusively","Blocks potassium channels exclusively","Blocks sodium and potassium channels"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EClass 1a antiarrhythmic drugs work by \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking both sodium and potassium channels\u003C/strong\u003E. This dual action results in prolongation of the action potential duration and increased effective refractory period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks sodium channels exclusively\u003C/strong\u003E: This better describes class 1b and 1c antiarrhythmic drugs, which have minimal effects on potassium channels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks beta-adrenergic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E: This describes class 2 antiarrhythmic drugs such as propranolol, which work by reducing sympathetic effects on the heart.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks calcium channels exclusively\u003C/strong\u003E: This is the mechanism of class 4 antiarrhythmic drugs such as verapamil, which primarily affect the atrioventricular node.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks potassium channels exclusively\u003C/strong\u003E: This is the mechanism of class 3 antiarrhythmic drugs such as amiodarone, which primarily affect repolarisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe sodium channel blockade slows conduction velocity, while potassium channel blockade prolongs repolarisation. Together these effects help suppress abnormal cardiac rhythms. Examples of class 1a drugs include quinidine, procainamide, and disopyramide.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Class 1a antiarrhythmic drugs block sodium channels and potassium channels, prolonging the action potential duration.","Examples of class 1a antiarrhythmic drugs include quinidine, procainamide, and disopyramide.","Class 1a antiarrhythmic drugs slow conduction velocity and increase the effective refractory period."],"references":["Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), Loke YK, MacEwan DJ, Robinson ESJ, et al. Rang and Dale\u2019s pharmacology. Tenth edition. London: Elsevier; 2024. (Pharmacology)."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62524"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17112"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62524","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62524"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T22:29:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T22:30:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9802"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77018"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"m